Name: Italy 10-year Government Bond Yield (with GFD Extension)
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1310 To Nov 1807
Monthly From Dec 1807 To Nov 1983
Weekly From Dec 1983 To Dec 1988
Daily From Jan 1989 To Mar 2022
Metadata:
Sources: Paul Schmelzing, Eight Centuries of Global Real interest Rates, R-G, and the 'suprasecular' decline, 1311-2018,' Bank of England Staff Working Paper No. 845; The Economist (1863-1914), La Riforma Sociale (1900-1923), League of Nations (1924-45), Bruno Bianchi, Appendice statistica: Il rendimento del consolidato dal 1862 al 1946, Capitale Industriale e Capitale Finanziario: Il Caso Italiano, Bologna: Societa Editrice il Mulino, 1979; Banca d'Italia, Bolletino (1946-)
Notes: Annual data from 1310 to 1806 is taking from Schmelzing. Naples 6% Consolidated Bond traded in Amsterdam (BGNAP6-AM) is used from November 1807 to January 1814, the Naples 5% Bond traded in Amsterdam (BGNAP5-AM) is used from February 1814 to December 1834, the Rome 5% Bonds of 1831 and 1845 (BGITROM531-PA) is used from January 1835 to December 1861. The Italian Rentes (BGITAR-ML) are used from January 1862 to October 1954 for domestic bond yields. The Rentes paid 5% interest from 1862 to June 1906, 3.75% from July 1906 to 1911, and 3.5% beginning in 1912. External bond yields are provided by the Italy 5%-3.75%-3.5% Rentes of 1861, first quoted in Paris (BGITA5-PA) from August 1861 to February 1863, and then in London (BGITA561-LO). The yields differ from the Italian yields after World War I because of exchange rate fluctuations.
For domestic yields, the 3.5% consol is used from 1900 until 1953, and the 5% reconstruction loan of 1978 is used beginning in 1954. An index of government treasury bonds begins in 1955. The average maturity of these bonds is six years.
